Activation functions

Activation functions a=g(z).

For output layer, σ works to map between 0−1:

σ(z)=11+e−z

Mean of data closer to zero with tanh, usually works better than σ as a hidden layer:

tanh⁡(z)=ez−e−zez+e−z

The rectified linear unit:

ReLU(z)=max(0,z)

The leaky ReLU:

Leaky ReLU(z)=max(0.01z,z)

For different activation functions g[1] for first hidden layer, g[2] for second hidden layer, etc.

Rules to choose activation functions:

  • If output is {0,1}, i.e. binary classification, sigmoid is a natural choice for the output layer σ. For all other layers, ReLU is a good choice.

Derivatives

σ′(z)=σ(z)(1−σ(z))tanh′⁡(z)=1−tanh⁡(z)2ReLU′={0if z<01if z>0undefif z=0Leaky ReLU′={0.01if z<01if z>0undefif z=0

Cost function

Here we use the cross-entropy loss, or log-loss L.

4 μs

L(y^,y)=−(ylog⁡(y^)+(1−y)log⁡(1−y^))

2 μs

L2 Regularization

λ2∑ℓ=1L‖w[ℓ]‖F2

Frobenius norm formula:

‖w[ℓ]‖F2=∑i=1n[ℓ]∑j=1n[ℓ−1](wi,j[ℓ])2

Gradient descent parameter update

Update the weights W and biases b using gradient descent with a learning rate α.

W[ℓ]←W[ℓ]−α(dW[ℓ])b[ℓ]←b[ℓ]−α(db[ℓ])

4.2 μs

Include L2 regularization term in gradient update.

W[ℓ]←W[ℓ]−α[(dW[ℓ])+λmW[ℓ]]

2.7 μs

Training the model

Initialize weights W and biases b.

  • Forward pass given inputs X

  • Backpropagation using outputs AN=Y^

  • Gradient descent update of parameters W and b

  • Repeat.
